definition.value: An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of threonine at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of threonine by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing threonine residues.
A benzaldehyde compound having a methyl group in an unspecified position.
Any member of the class of benzenes that is a substituted benzene in which the substituents include one (and only one) methyl group.
A L-proline derivative that is L-proline substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 4 (the 3S,4S diastereoisomer).
An element whose atom has an incomplete d sub-shell, or which can give rise to cations with an incomplete d sub-shell.
A disaccharide formed by a (1<->1)-glycosidic bond between two units of D-glucose.
An oxoacid containing three carboxy groups.
Any one of the six possible isomers of trichlorophenol.
A chemical compound containing three hydroxy groups.
A  tertiary amine that is ethanolamine having two N-methyl substituents.

An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of tryptophan  at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of tryptophan  by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing tryptophan residues.
Aralkylamino compounds which contain a tyramine skeleton.
A proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of L-tyrosine at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of L-tyrosine by a heteroatom.
Any fatty acid containing at least one C=C or C#C bond.
An oxopurine that is the final oxidation product of purine metabolism.
A derivative of uridine, bearing an additional carboxymethoxy substituent at position 5 on the uracil ring.
A methyl ester that is uridine which is substituted at position 5 on the uracil ring by a methoxycarbonylmethoxy group.
An monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of urocanic acid.
An alpha,beta-unsaturated monocarboxylic acid that is prop-2-enoic acid substituted by a 1H-imidazol-4-yl group at position 3. It is a metabolite of hidtidine.
A carbohydrate acid formally derived by oxidation to a carboxy group of the terminal -CH2OH group of any aldose or ketose.
A branched-chain amino acid that consists of glycine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the alpha-carbon is substituted by an isopropyl group.

An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of valine at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of valine  by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing valine  residues.
A fatty acid which has a chain length greater than C22.

An epoxycarotenol that is 5,5',6,6'-tetrahydro-5,6:5',6'-diepoxy-beta,beta-carotene substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 3'. It is the naturally occurring xanthophyll pigment found in a variety of plants.
A subclass of carotenoids consisting of the oxygenated carotenes.
The O-hydroxy(phenyl)phosphinoyl derivative of ecgonine methyl ester.
A neutral compound having formal unit electrical charges of opposite sign on non-adjacent atoms. Sometimes referred to as inner salts, dipolar ions (a misnomer).
Belonging to the inositol family of compounds, D-chiro-inositol (DCI) is an isomer of glucose. It is an important secondary messenger in insulin signal transduction.
A chlorocarbon that is methane in which all the hydrogens have been replaced by chloro groups.
A monocarboxylic acid that consists of acrylic acid bearing a phenyl substituent at the 3-position. It is found in Cinnamomum cassia.
